<author><name><![CDATA[Bregalad]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-07-16T00:56:41-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-07-16T00:56:41-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6605&amp;p=64329#p64329</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6605&amp;p=64329#p64329"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Final Fantasy NES: 4 distinct character palettes]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6605&amp;p=64329#p64329"><![CDATA[
I think in fact FF1 and FF2 uses two palettes for characters and two for weapons/effects (remember damage is shown in a caption box NOT sprites), and FF3 improved it to have weapons+effects+damage using one palette, leaving 3 for characters.<br /><br />So the best thing possible would be to hack FF1 to do it FF3-style. Then, technically, it should be possible to rewrite character 1's palette right after character 1 to match character 4's colors. Definitely not easy to do without too much graphical glitches, even harder to implement in FF1's code, but technically possible.<br />If it's too hard to hack FF1's palette so they are used in FF3-style, then this technique can be used 2 times - rewrite character 1's palette with character 3's and character 2's palette with character 4's.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Fri Jul 16, 2010 12:56 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
